{"/service/ndnp/ak/batch_ak_kingcrab_ver03/data/sn87062011/00414185836/1914032501/0476.xml":{"full_text":"THE\nHowe Daily R*Met\nAN INDEPENDENT NEWEPAPBB\nPabUshed delly except Sunday by\nNOME PUBLISHING CO.\na C. DIVINE\nOBO. 5. MAYNARD\nSole Owners and Publishers\nRICHARD HATTON, Ed^ur.\nEUMCRIPTION RATES\n(In advance.)\nNome Dally Nunet 1 month....9t.M\nNome Dally Nunet months. 110.00\nNome Dally Nonet. 1 year.5*0.09\nNome Weekly Nonet 1 month...60c\nNome-Wookly Nonet. 1 year...1800\nNUGGET MINING AND ORBDGING\nMAGAZINE.\n(Issued Annually In October.)\nPrice per copy.Mo\nPrice per oopy. mailed.50c\nRates for advert lain* space In any\nof the nhoro publications will bo made\nknown on application.\nPHONB MAIN Of.\n_n_.^^d.eUaa mailae VdK\n24, 1MT. at the Postofflce at Nome,\nAlaska, uader the Act of Congress of\nMarch ft. 1171.\nCopy for regular advertlaaments\nmust be la by 10 o\u2019clock on the day\nof publication.\nFIRE ALARM SIGNALS\nIS.Standard Oil Co\nIS.Carstena Cold Storage\n14.J. J. Seanon Co., office\nlft. Headquarters Saloon\n21. Recorders Office\n24 Pioneers Igloo\n25 Fro Department\n21 .Discovery Saloon\n22 Torkey\u2019s Cigar Store\n41 .Pacific Cold Storage, Sandaplt\n42 .Third Ave. and Lanes Way\nEngine House. Phone Main 17\n7 whistles water 2. fire out\nOffiftial Paptr\nNOME, ALASKA, MARCH 29, 1914.\nA great many people in a great\nmany different walks of life arc con\ntinually. contributing money to for\neign missions. Othar good people\ntravel afar to foreign lansd and give\ntheir lives to the service of teaching\nthe Christian faith to people who may\nor may not need It. Whether the\nforeign missionaries are accomplish\ning any amount of good in all of the\nlands where they are stationed la a\nmatter open to a great deal of argu\nment pro and con and also one which\nwill have to be taken from a good\nmany different points of view.\nWhether the money and the lives\nspent In carrying the Christian faith\nto all of the people of the so-called\nbenighted races might not be better\nspent In lightening the burden right\nhere at home Is also a matter which\nmust be viewed frSm many different\nangles. There are many very good\npeople, religious people, good Chris\ntians who believe that there is enough\nwork and enough charity to be don*\nright here In these United States to\nkeep all hands busy on tho Job with\nout seeking far afield for objects of\nconversion and of assistance of a more\nmaterial kind.\nBe that aa It may there have also\nmaisu mass awaoIIah# MOAnln\nmho have gone In for the conversion\nand education of the \"heathen'* and\nthey have undoubtedly done a great\ndeal of good. They have also done a\ngreat deal of harm, but the good is\nvery probably in the preponderance.\nIn China for example there hnve\nbeen a great many Christian mission\naries of a great many creeds and\nmore especially from America there\nhave gone medical missionaries who\nmost certainly have been of great\nbenefit to the people's bodily nllmenti\nIf they have not accomplished so mueii\nwith their souls.\nThis Is what the greatest statesman\nthat China has yet produced. M Hunn\nChang, who was at one time the Chi\nnese minister to the United States\nthinks About Christianity. His vlewi\narc recorded In his memories and hr\nnays that there is no reason for hat\ning Christians. Devotsd ns he Is In\nmind nnd In spirit, hy sentiment and\ni y reason to the teachings of Con\nfucius. he Is now ready to pine*\nJesus Christ on ths same exalted level\nwith China's hero-sags, says the Rsv\nC. F. Aked. Li says that had ha live*\nin America, or Europe ns s youth ht\nwould hnvo been u follower of Jesus\nChrist, us In China he follows Con\nfucius. Ho snys that there are mil\nlions of his countrymen who would he\nbettor for Christianity.\nWhat a spirit is this for a \u2022\u2022heath\nen;\" What tolerance for the religion\nof another rnee and whnt a great big\nsouled man must be be who can say\nthat millions of his people would be\nbetter for tho religion of Christians.\nThat had he Known of Christ at the\ntime he was accepting a religion he\nbight have followed tho Christian\nleader Instead of Confucius.\nWhat devout Christian has a soul\nbig enough to admit that there is\ngood In other religions than his own.\nthat some people of tho Christian\ncountries might bo better off If they\nfollowed the teachings of a heathen\nprophet.\nMighty few are the Christians who\nare board enough to take a view of\nthat kind.\nAnd yet how many Christians would\nrot be belter off It they followed the\nfaith of Mohamet In so far as abstin\nence from nil forms of alcohol are\nconcerned. How many Christians arc\nus devout In their dally men and fol\nI >wa tha fuith ns do the Mohamedans.\nFew Indeed.\nThere uro things in the icllgion of\nthat same Confucius who is the god\nof a large part of the Chinese that It\nwculd benefit ft Christian to know and\nto follow. There arc things In the\nfaith of Zoraster and of Buddha and\nof Tao that might be appropriated\n_\u25b2 manv mnnv nofl\nTV Ik II QIVOV\npie who today are self satisfied and\nsnug in the belief that because they\nthe followers of the Christian faith\nthey are therefore far better people\nthan all of the poor believers In other\nprophets nnd other gods.\nIt is an egotistical nnd absurd idea\nthat the nvernge so-called Christian\nis a better man or a better woman\nthan the despised \"heathen.\"\nWhen It comes right down to cases\nthe \u201cheathen\" in nine times out of\nten is the better of the two. no mat\nter what his religion, because lie does\nwhat the nvernge so-called Christian\ndecs not do. He lives his religion.\nHr Is taught the way he should go\nnnd then he goes it from the cmdle to\nthe grave. On the other hnnd the\nChristian, u great many Christians,\nere diligently shown the way and then\nas diligently they wander off into the\nl yways of desire and self indulgence\nnd they become liypocratis because\nti hide their wonderlngs.\nPerhaps if some of the good mls\n*1- narks who spend their lives trying\nto nvert |*oople of other faiths who\narc (olte satisfied with what they\nhave and who arc living noble lb es\nwhich will in the end take them to the\nsame heaven that the Christians ire\nbound for, would let the \"heathen\u201d\nalone and go after some of the wan\ndering brothers of their own faith\nthey would be doing the human race\na greater benefit and, after all the\ntest in all religions is the good done\nto fellow man.\nThe refusal of the British govern\nment to be officially represented at\nthe Pan-American fair nt San Fran\ncisco in 1915, does not mean that\nGreat Britain will not be represented\nat tl.c exhibition; nor docs it mean,\nas r. section of the American press\nv bid lend us to believe, that Great\nBritain is unfriendly to the Unlto-1\nStates nnd her commercial projects.\nGreat Britain at first refused to bo\nofficially represented nt the St. Louis\ne\\hibltion In 1901, and only consent\ned when the commercial interests of\nthe United Kingdom Insisted that It\nwould benefit the trade of the country\nto have a government display.\nThen ns now enterprising firms that\nwanted to ploy the game with their\nrivals on the continent brought pres\nsure to bear on the government. <t\ndoes not seem, however, that lhe gov\nernment Is giving a vory attentive\nout to the domnnd of commerce In this\nInstance. Probably the fact tliat the\n(luestion of the tolls on coast shipping\nbus not yet been settled by the Amer\nican government has something to do\nwith the determination of Great Bri\ntain to stand aloof from the fair, but\nIn the opinion of the captains of com\nmerce even unfair treatment In the\nmatter of tolls should not stand In the\nway of a big official British exhibit.\nNo matter what decision the Amerl\nIcan government arrives nt In regard\nto the coastwise trade. Great Britain\nand the colonies of Great Britain\nstand to gain more by live opening of\ntin canal than any other country. At\nthe present time the mother country\nhas the lion\u2019s shnre of the trade with\nChile; she has a went commerce with\nTern. Ecuador and Colombia and other\nSouth and Central American countries\non tho Pacific and she has her trade\nwith Western Canada, which with a\nshort sea route can nnd will bo made\nmuch greater than It la nt present.\nIt Is said Hint England and Germany\nhave an understanding not to bo rep\nresented at the fair. If this 4s ao\nEngland Is making a gross blunder\nGermany does not want to bo repre\nsented because she has no money tr\n\u25a0pure, but Great Britain lias and the\nexpedlture of the couple of mllllo.-t\ndollars, which the board of trade nam\ned as necessary, would not be felt by\nthe nation and would bring a multi\nfold roturn. A year ago the absence\nof England and Germany from tho\ngreat fair would have been Incon\nceivable. It Is almost Inconceivable\nnow, but we may bo sure that If the\ngovernments of thoso countries do not\nrealise the advantage of being repre\nsented, their great Industrial firms will.\nVancouver Sun.\nThe business depression which la\nsweeping the country at this time ?a\nbeing used effectively und diabolically\nby pollticana nnd antl?admlntatratlon\nnewspapers to atlr up anti-Wilson\nsentiment.\n'Tla true, the country, is now Juat In\nthe throes of readjustment. But Pres\nident Wilson did not create the situa\ntion. The blame lies on the shoulders\nof those responsible for the sixteen\nyears of riotous, crooked high finance\nwhich antedated 1913. Republican\nmeasures, beginning with the late\nMark Hanna's nsccndency In Walh\nIngto nin 189C and continuing up to\nand Including the last days of the\nTaft administration In 1912, are re\nsponsible.\nIt Is as unfair to assume that this\ncountry la suffering nt this moment\nfrom tho acts of the present chief ex\n....tt,,. nm it irnnid ito to sav that the\nparalysis which ha sjust been visited\nupon the decrepit old man next door\nhas been caused by the food he haa\nlenten this yonr at his new hotel. The\ncauses and the foundation for his\nparalysis of this year happened and\nwere laid years ago by ether heredity\nor wrong habits and his habits of thla\nyear connot be distorted into even a\nsuperinducing cause for his malody.\nHad Mr. Taft succeeded himself, the\npresent business depression might\nhave been headed off for a short pe\nriod, but eventually there would have\nbeen a cataclysm that would have\nengulfed the nntlon.\ntVe are now suffering for the sins\nof our forbears.\nSome of our suffering, indeed. Is\nvicarious, because posterity shall be\nan extent be tlic beneficiary. But\nsurely, none of this generation has\ncause to lament the fact that a halt\nhas been called on the 16-year-ol<l\nJuggernaut that, under the guise of\nprosperity, was gradually enslaving\nthe nation.\nThe era of financial license and\nlibldinoutness has abrutlv ended and\nthe country Is suffering from the\nshock. But it is certainly hitter that\nthe end should be now and that the\nnow reckoning should commence this\nyear thnn that the Incvltablo be post\nponed.\u2014Ex.\nWHY EAT POOR BREAD.\nWhen you can gat GOOD, WHOLE\nSOME Bread at 5c par loaf.\nANVIL BAKERY,\nNORTH POLE BAKERY.\nMrs. Bartlett\u2019s dancing class svory\nTuesday and Friday evenings at 8\np. m. K. K. hall, children\u2019s Saturday\nafternoons.\n___\nSubscribe for Nome Daily Nugget\nProfessional Cards\nTHIS SPACE RESERVED.\nTHIS SPACE RESERVED.\n||HIIIIIIHtllimt\u2018\u201c>*J\nI DOG\njj SALMON\n8c per lb. at\nBESSIE STORE\n\n9\nBrtaMI\u00abh\u00abf Jut\nmu Biotieg art\nSite Pepflsit (apy\nPaid-Up Capita 9129,000\nA E\u2014fl\nNiitfs NcrdMDts\nBale of Aliski\nNOME. ALASKA\nCapital $100,000\n(iSold Dust Purchased\nand Assayed\nI Marks Rsadhsas*\nTHE PLACE TO ETOP AT IN\nCOUNCIL\nGOOD ROOMS\nCLEAN BEDS\nFIRST CLASS MEAL*\nR. M. MORRISON, Pr*\u00bb\nCOUNCIL, ALASKA\ni\n4 4\nI\n4\n4 4\n4\n4 4\n4 4\n4 4\nOPEN OAY AND NIOHT.\n4 4\nBpaeial Hama Mad# Tamala**\nNext Door to Pacific Cold\nStorage market\n